          Russia’s Defense Ministry <a href="https://www.dw.com/en/ukraine-updates-russia-claims-further-advances-in-donetsk/live-71060919" target="_blank">announced</a> the capture of two villages, Vesely Gai and Pushkine, in Ukraine’s eastern <a href="https://www.google.com/maps/place/Donetsk,+Donetsk+Oblast,+Ukraine,+83000/@47.9902294,37.596709,11z/data=!4m15!1m8!3m7!1s0x40e0909500919a2d:0x36335efdc5856f84!2sDonetsk,+Donetsk+Oblast,+Ukraine,+83000!3b1!8m2!3d48.015883!4d37.80285!16zL20vMDJxYnBk!3m5!1s0x40e0909500919a2d:0x36335efdc5856f84!8m2!3d48.015883!4d37.80285!16zL20vMDJxYnBk?entry=ttu&g_ep=EgoyMDI0MTIxMS4wIKXMDSoASAFQAw%3D%3D" target="_blank">Donetsk</a> region. This signaled an acceleration in Moscow’s advance toward the key logistical hub of Pokrovsk and the industrial town of Kurakhove. Ukraine’s Khortytsia group reported “exhausting clashes” near Kurakhove, Chasiv Yar, and surrounding areas. They describe the situation as “complex and changing,” with Ukrainian forces working to improve their tactical positions. The Donetsk region is a contested front in the ongoing conflict.</p>
        </mj-text>
