          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">What is the Maghreb?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopolitics.world/email/images/gp-dec-17-3.jpg" alt="What is the Maghreb?" href="https://www.geopolitics.world" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Maghreb" target="_blank">Maghreb</a>, which means “the west” in Arabic, refers to Northwest Africa, which comprises Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia, Libya, and Mauritania. Nestled between the Atlantic Ocean, the Mediterranean Sea, and the Sahara Desert, this region is a geographic and cultural bridge between Europe, sub-Saharan Africa, and the Arab world.</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Culturally, the Maghreb reflects a rich tapestry woven from Arab, Berber, and Islamic influences, with Arabic and Berber languages shaping its identity. In most of these, French is a significant language due to the region’s colonial history, particularly in Algeria, Morocco, and Tunisia. The Maghreb has historically been a hub of trade and intellectual exchange, with cities like Marrakech and Tunis serving as vibrant centers of art, learning, and commerce under powerful dynasties like the Almoravids and Almohads.​</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">In modern times, the Maghreb plays a critical geopolitical role as a link between continents. The region deals with regional tensions, migration issues, and economic integration. To mitigate some of these challenges, it has a small union called the <a href="https://maghrebarabe.org/en/" target="_blank">Maghreb Union</a>. The Maghreb’s unique location and rich history make it a vital cultural and strategic region, embodying centuries of interaction between Africa, Europe, and the Arab world.​</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
